        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">How long does dental SEO take to show results?<span class="faq-icon"><svg><use href="#i-plus"/></svg></span></button>
          <div class="faq-answer">60–90 days for initial ranking movement. 3–6 months for meaningful traffic growth. 6–12 months for compounding results significantly impacting new patient volume. Timeline depends on local competition, website authority, and publishing consistency. Thirty articles monthly shows faster results than 2–4 articles.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Is Google Business Profile enough for dental SEO?<span class="faq-icon"><svg><use href="#i-plus"/></svg></span></button>
          <div class="faq-answer">GBP is necessary but insufficient. Optimized GBP with regular posts helps rank in local 3-pack for "dentist near me." But it doesn't help rank for informational queries like "dental implants cost" or "invisalign vs braces." Those require blog content on your website. Complete strategy combines GBP activity with blog content.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Can I do dental SEO myself without any tools?<span class="faq-icon"><svg><use href="#i-plus"/></svg></span></button>
          <div class="faq-answer">Technically yes. Write blog posts, create GBP updates, submit to directories, respond to reviews — all manually. But it requires 15–25 hours monthly, time most dentists don't have between patients. The question isn't whether you can; it's whether your time is better spent on patients or blog posts.</div>
